			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2016</a> paper:</span><br><i>FRaMED: Full-Fledge Role Modeling Editor (Tool Demo)</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ThomasKühn.html">Thomas Kühn</a>, <a href="../profile/KayBierzynski.html">Kay Bierzynski</a>, <a href="../profile/SebastianRichly.html">Sebastian Richly</a>, <a href="../profile/UweAßmann.html">Uwe Aßmann</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2997364.2997371">10.1145/2997364.2997371</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It presents an editor/tool for role modeling—i.e., language workbench-style tooling for a modeling language.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> Role modeling is supported through a graphical editor/notation, emphasizing visualization.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The tool targets a specific modeling language (role modeling) in a DSL/DSML setting.
</li></ul></li></ul>
